This paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it introduces a post-processing algorithm to compress the learned SVM model. Additionally, the paper evaluates the algorithm on several real-world data sets, which is a common practice in machine learning research. The paper may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category as SVMs are a popular machine learning technique used in AI applications. The paper may also be relevant to computer vision (cs.CV) as SVMs are commonly used in image classification tasks. The paper may also be relevant to data structures (cs.DS) as the algorithm involves reducing and optimizing support vectors. Finally, the paper may be relevant to neural networks (cs.NE) as SVMs are sometimes used as a component in neural network architectures.
